{
  "concept": "vuejs/core#6063: Using whitespace \"preserve\" wont compile v-if/v-else using same slot name",
  "version": "1.0",
  "created_at": "2026-03-15T04:26:10.630791+00:00",
  "text": "Using whitespace \"preserve\" wont compile v-if/v-else using same slot name\n\n### Vue version\n\n3.2.37\n\n### Link to minimal reproduction\n\nhttps://github.com/jesusgn90/issue-whitespace\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nRun the project \r\n```\r\nyarn\r\nyarn dev\r\n```\r\n\r\nSee the console\n\n### What is expected?\n\nNo error is shown\n\n### What is actually happening?\n\nIs showing an error that it should not, and is not compiling the template properly\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8860227/172195847-1ba18a3d-13e6-47f3-b6ed-253edfc4ba1a.png)\r\n\r\n\r\nthis is valid code that should compile and it's not\r\n```vue\r\n  <HelloWorld>\r\n    <template v-if=\"true\" #buttons>\r\n      <h1>Hello World</h1>\r\n    </template>\r\n    <template v-else=\"false\" #buttons>\r\n      <h1>Hello World</h1>\r\n    </template>\r\n  </HelloWorld>\r\n```\n\n### System Info\n\n```shell\nI do not think this applies here but...\r\n\r\n<details>\r\n  System:\r\n    OS: Linux 5.13 Pop!_OS 20.04 LTS\r\n    CPU: (8) x64 Intel(R) Core(TM) i7-7700HQ CPU @ 2.80GHz\r\n    Memory: 676.01 MB / 31.27 GB\r\n    Container: Yes\r\n    Shell: 5.0.17 - /bin/bash\r\n  Binaries:\r\n    Node: 16.13.0 - /usr/local/bin/node\r\n    Yarn: 1.22.15 - ~/.yarn/bin/yarn\r\n    npm: 8.1.0 - /usr/local/bin/npm\r\n  Browsers:\r\n    Brave Browser: 92.1.27.111\r\n    Chrome: 101.0.4951.41\r\n    Chromium: 83.0.4103.116\r\n    Firefox: 96.0\r\n    Firefox Nightly: 97.0a1\r\n  npmPackages:\r\n    vue: ^3.2.25 => 3.2.37 \r\n</details>\n```\n\n\n### Any additional comments?\n\nI tested this with the `vue-cli` as well, so it's not related to `vite` vs `vue-cli`, the problem resides on `@vue/compiler-core` potentially, and I suspect this is the problem:\r\n\r\nSince both `template` nodes are using the same slot name (`#buttons`), it thinks they are the `same` node so when it reaches the second node (the one using `v-else-if`) there is no previous node using the `v-if` because it just _replaced_ the previous node.",
  "language": "en",
  "keywords": [
    "scope: compiler",
    "has PR",
    "🔩 p2-edge-case"
  ],
